# CI/CD Guidelines

## Pipeline Principles
- Every change goes through a pull request; no direct pushes to main
- CI runs on every PR: lint, validate, test, security scan
- CD only triggers on merge to main (or release branch)
- Deployments are automated but gated: require approval for production
- Pipelines must be reproducible and idempotent
- Every deployment must map to a commit SHA — log version, environment, and artifact for traceability

## Infrastructure Pipeline (Terraform)

### Validation (PR triggers)
- `terraform init` with correct backend config (must succeed before any other step)
- `terraform fmt -check`, `terraform validate`, `terraform plan`
- Security scan: `checkov` / `tfsec`
- Policy enforcement: fail pipeline on violations (no public S3, no open SGs, no wildcard IAM)
- Cost estimation: surface cost diff in PR (Infracost or equivalent)
- Post plan output as PR comment for reviewer visibility

### Plan Review
- Reviewer must validate terraform plan output (not just code diff)
- Explicitly check: resource changes, deletions, replacements
- Highlight destructive changes (replace, destroy) — require explicit approval

### State & Drift
- Must use remote backend (S3 + DynamoDB lock)
- State locking must be enabled — no local state in CI/CD
- Each environment must have separate state file, backend config, and variables — no shared state between environments
- Drift detection: plan against remote state before apply; surface drift in PR or pipeline logs
- Scheduled drift checks (weekly/daily) on production to catch out-of-band changes
- No manual state manipulation without documented justification
- Emergency manual changes must be followed by reconciliation via Terraform — drift must be resolved in code, not ignored

### Concurrency
- Only one apply per environment at a time
- Use GitHub Actions concurrency groups: `concurrency: { group: terraform-${{ env }}, cancel-in-progress: false }`
- Queue, don't cancel — infra applies must not be interrupted mid-execution

### Apply
- Apply only after PR approval and merge
- Apply must use the same commit SHA as the reviewed plan — no re-plan drift between approval and apply without visibility
- Use separate pipelines per environment/layer
- Never auto-apply to production without human approval
- Avoid destructive changes without explicit reviewer sign-off on plan
- Set `timeout-minutes` on apply jobs — Terraform can hang on provider/network issues; fail safely
- Log applied changes and outputs; store apply logs as pipeline artifacts
- Record: commit SHA, environment, resources changed — for audit and debugging

### Caching
- Cache Terraform providers and modules (`actions/cache` on `.terraform/`)
- Reduces init time and provider download flakiness

## Application Pipeline
- Build → Test → Scan → Push Image → Deploy Staging → Deploy Production
- Tag images with git SHA (not `latest`)
- Push images to ECR; use immutable tags
- Run security scans (Trivy, Snyk) on container images
- Use rolling deployments with health checks
- Cache build dependencies (node_modules, pip packages, Go modules)

## Environment Promotion
- Non-production deploys automatically on merge to main
- Production deploys require GitHub Environment approval
- Use the same image/artifact across all environments; only config differs
- Never rebuild artifacts for production; promote the tested artifact

## Security & Secrets
- Use OIDC for cloud credentials in CI/CD; no stored access keys
- Use least-privilege GitHub Actions permissions; restrict default `GITHUB_TOKEN` scopes
- Declare explicit `permissions:` block in every workflow (never rely on defaults)
- Store application secrets in AWS Secrets Manager
- Inject secrets at runtime, never bake into images
- Rotate CI/CD credentials on a schedule

## Failure Handling
- Pipeline failure must include: logs, failing step, and error context
- Infrastructure failures must not auto-retry blindly — require manual review for failed applies
- Detect stuck pipelines: set `timeout-minutes` on all jobs; kill and alert if exceeded
- Application deploy failures: auto-rollback if health checks fail within timeout
- Alert on pipeline failures (Slack/Datadog integration)

## Rollback
- Application: revert the PR or redeploy previous image tag
- Infrastructure: revert Terraform code and re-apply (plan + review + apply cycle)
- Database: use migration rollback scripts; never drop in production
- Document rollback procedures in runbooks
